2026-04-16 12:39:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['timing potentiometer wiper connection / associated PCB trace or solder joint in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that the timing potentiometer’s two end terminals are correctly at ~12 V and 0 V, but the wiper is electrically disconnected (open circuit) and never develops any voltage regardless of shaft rotation. The control module otherwise has proper 12 V supply and correct polarity, yet its output remains stuck at a small low-level voltage (~0.36 V) and never drives the relay to the rails in response to light changes. An open wiper (or its PCB/solder connection) breaks the feedback/control path that sets the relay timing and threshold, leaving the control electronics biased in an abnormal state that keeps the relay drive near a small offset voltage. This explains both the prior intermittent blinking and the current failure to switch properly. Repairing or replacing the faulty timing potentiometer wiper connection (or its PCB trace/solder pad) should restore normal control-module operation.'
