2026-04-16 12:39:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module sensitivity potentiometer', 'control (ambient sensor) module sensitivity potentiometer wiper connection / associated PCB trace or solder joint'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module has correct supply rails (≈12 V and 0 V) and all passive parts already checked (sensor bias resistor, sensor, relay coil/contacts, wiring) measure nominal. Yet the entire sensor/timing network node sits clamped around 0.12–0.36 V and does not respond to light or to timing‑pot adjustments. The timing potentiometer’s end terminals are at 12 V and 0 V, but its wiper was found disconnected during measurement and repairing its connection did not restore operation; therefore the timing pot is not the element that should be controlling the comparator threshold in this design, but rather the sensitivity potentiometer is. If the sensitivity potentiometer wiper/track is open or its terminals mis‑soldered, the comparator input node that should be biased between 0 and 12 V collapses toward ground through the sensor, creating the observed ~0.1–0.36 V on the entire low‑side node. This explains: (1) the constant low output of the control module (≈0.36 V on the ‘+’ output even with full supply present internally), (2) lack of response to ambient‑light changes, and (3) lack of effect from timing‑pot adjustments, while the relay, sensor, and wiring remain healthy. Hence the most plausible remaining root cause is an internal open/misconnection in the sensitivity potentiometer or its wiper-to-comparator PCB trace in the control module.'
