2026-04-16 12:40:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module ground / negative output wiring between module and load', 'load module input cable polarity / connector pairing between control output and load input'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal components of the control module (relay, driver, sensor, timing and sensitivity potentiometers, bias resistor, sensor, and PCB traces) have now been tested and either behave nominally or have been explicitly repaired with no effect. Yet the measured ‘+’ control output sits at about 0.36 V while the ‘−’ output is at ~0 V, and the lamp previously blinked every 20 s before later tests where the lamp stayed off when the timing pot was moved.\n\nThe only remaining consistent explanation is a wiring/configuration fault external to the active circuitry: the return/negative path between the control module and the load module is mis‑wired. Either the control module negative output lead is not actually connected to the load module negative input lead, or the fast‑connection terminals between control and load are paired incorrectly so that the lamp/diode network is referenced to the wrong node (e.g., floating at ~0.36 V rather than solid ground). This would cause the control module to see 12 V internally (as measured) but the load module to receive only a small differential voltage, producing intermittent or no lamp operation and making the measured control outputs appear stuck near 0.36 V above the true return.\n\nBecause all electronic components have been largely ruled out, the fault is most plausibly a misconnections of the cables between the control module outputs and the load module inputs, particularly involving the negative/ground conductor or polarity at that interface.'
