DESCRIPTION: With power removed, disconnect at least one leg of the timing potentiometer from the PCB and measure its resistance between the two end terminals and between each end and the wiper to confirm it is a functional pot (end‑to‑end resistance and smooth wiper change). Then, still unpowered, use the ohmmeter to map where each of the three potentiometer pins actually goes on the PCB: identify which pin connects to +12 V rail, which to negative rail/ground, and which to the timing/comparator node. Compare this pinout and wiring to the schematic symbol orientation to detect whether the timing pot has been mis‑oriented or mis‑wired (e.g., wiper tied permanently to one rail or wrong node).,
RESULT: No resistance/continuity measurements were obtained: the timing potentiometer and all listed modules report “no resistance parameter,” so their resistance cannot be tested in this environment. Consequently, the timing pot’s functionality and pin mapping relative to the schematic could not be verified from these steps.
