2026-04-16 12:40:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module timing potentiometer wiring / node assignment (mis‑wired to +12 V and ground, not to the timing/comparator node)'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components in the control module (sensor, relay, comparator/driver, supply rails, input/output wiring, and both potentiometers themselves) have now been tested or even replaced and found good. The module input has a correct 12 V, but the output never moves from about 0.36 V on the positive side and ≈0 V on the negative side, regardless of ambient light or the timing pot position. Measurements show the timing pot end terminals at ≈12 V and 0 V, but the wiper is effectively disconnected from the rest of the circuit in operation: there is no observable wiper voltage and its continuity/path could not be mapped in the test environment. This behavior is exactly what would occur if the timing pot were mis‑wired or mis‑placed on the PCB so that its wiper pin is not actually connected to the intended timing/comparator node, but instead the comparator/timing node is incorrectly tied to the low bias node around 0.12–0.36 V. That would clamp the control node to a small offset above ground, preventing the comparator from ever driving the relay or output toward the 12 V rail, and would also explain the earlier observed ~20 s blinking as the network occasionally charges/discharges through leakage. Since individual component faults have been ruled out, the remaining plausible root cause is a wiring / node‑assignment error for the timing potentiometer within the control (ambient sensor) module, effectively leaving the control/timing node permanently near ground and the pot wiper not connected to the correct circuit node.'
