2026-04-16 12:41:41 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module output cables / connector polarity between power module and control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal circuitry of the control module measures as correctly powered: +12 V and 0 V rails are present and not inverted, and the sensor‑bias low node sits at ~0.12 V above the control‑module negative rail as expected. The relay, sensor, comparator/driver, timing and sensitivity networks all check nominal by prior tests and repair attempts.\n\nYet the control module output to the load never reaches the supply rails and instead sits at about +0.36 V relative to its own negative output. That is consistent with the control module “seeing” only a small voltage across its output pair rather than the full 12 V, i.e., one of its output terminals is effectively tied close to its own reference node instead of to the true 12 V rail.\n\nGiven that:\n- The power module LED shows the battery is present and correctly oriented inside the power module.\n- Measurements explicitly confirmed the correct polarity and amplitude between the power module’s internal rails and the control‑module input terminals.\n- No internal mis‑wiring or short to ground has been found within the control module despite extensive testing and even replacement of its active stages.\n\nThe remaining plausible fault consistent with all evidence is an external polarity/configuration error between the power‑supply module and the control module: the fast‑connection output cables from the power module are mis‑paired or reversed so that the control module’s “+12_in” and “−_in” terminals are not actually connected to the intended 12 V and 0 V nodes. Because the connectors are symmetric, it is possible to mate them such that both modules individually have internally correct polarity (power LED on) yet the series connection between modules leaves the control module seeing only a small differential (~0.36 V) at its output pair, causing the lamp to be unlit or to blink abnormally.\n\nThus the root cause is a polarity/connector pairing fault on the cables between the power supply module and the control (ambient sensor) module, not within the control module’s internal circuitry itself.'
