2026-04-16 12:42:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module light sensor element'] hypothesis_explanation='The power module and its polarity are correct (12 V present, LED on). The control module clearly has a valid 12 V supply rail, and its internal ground / reference wiring has been checked and found nominal. The relay coil sees nearly the full supply (≈11.99 V) with its low side at ≈0.36 V, so the output is being clamped low by the control circuitry and not by wiring or contact issues.\n\nAll timing and sensitivity potentiometer faults, relay driver/contact faults, PCB trace faults, and wiring/polarity issues between modules have already been ruled out by repair attempts that had no effect. The approximately 0.12 V node at the sensor‑bias low side shows that the bias resistor is dropping nearly the full 12 V across it, meaning almost no current flows through the sensor branch. That is consistent with an open or failed light sensor element (e.g., photodiode/phototransistor/LDR) rather than with mis‑biasing from other components that have already been tested or replaced.\n\nWith an open light sensor, the comparator input tied to the sensor node would sit at or near ground regardless of ambient light, preventing the output from ever driving the relay fully and leaving the relay low side floating around a small leakage level (~0.36 V). The earlier symptom of periodic 0.5‑s lamp dropouts can be explained by the timing network interacting with this starved sensor input, but once the pot was disturbed in testing the module settled into a state where the relay never fully energizes.\n\nGiven that: (1) supply rails and wiring are confirmed good, (2) the relay and driver are functional, (3) the timing and sensitivity pots and their wiring have been verified and/or replaced, and (4) the only remaining un-replaced element that directly controls the comparator input is the light sensor itself, the most plausible remaining root cause is a faulty or open light sensor element in the control (ambient sensor) module.'
