DESCRIPTION: With the control module powered and still disconnected from the load, probe the comparator/driver output node that drives the relay coil (or the transistor’s collector/emitter that connects to the relay negative terminal). Measure the DC voltage of this driver output relative to the module’s negative input while the sensor is alternately darkened and brightly illuminated. In the same conditions, directly measure the voltage across the relay coil itself (positive coil terminal to negative coil terminal). Report whether the driver output ever pulls the coil terminal close to ground (energizing the relay), whether it sits stuck near ~0.36 V, or whether the relay coil is permanently seeing only a small voltage difference.,
RESULT: The driver output node for the relay coil negative terminal is sitting at approximately 0.36 V relative to the module’s negative input in both sensor conditions and does not pull close to ground. The relay coil is seeing a nearly full supply voltage across it (about 11.99 V from positive to negative terminal) in both measurements.
