2026-04-16 12:43:21 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module main negative input reference / wiring relative to system ground (module internally referenced to external +12 V instead of 0 V)'] hypothesis_explanation='All individual components inside the control module (relay, driver, sensor, pots, PCB traces) have now been ruled out by targeted tests and replacement attempts, yet the module’s behavior remains that the output is stuck around +0.36 V with respect to the system negative and never swings to the rails. The relay coil sees nearly the full 12 V at all times, meaning it is effectively always energized, while the driver node that *should* pull the coil negative terminal near 0 V instead sits around +0.36 V. The sensor‑bias ‘low’ node is at about +0.12 V relative to the system negative and is resistively tied (~1.3 Ω) to the module’s negative input. This indicates that what the control circuit “thinks” is its ground / reference node is offset and is in fact referenced incorrectly to the external supply rails.\n\nTaken together, the only consistent explanation left is a configuration/wiring error at the level of the control module’s main reference: the module is internally using the external +12 V line as its logic reference (ground) and the external 0 V as its positive rail, or at least has its internal reference network mis‑assigned between these rails. That would cause all internal voltages to appear low and clamped when measured against the true system ground, and it would make the driver output incapable of pulling the relay terminal to the actual 0 V rail. The repeated component‑level checks and replacements failing to change behavior point away from a bad part and toward this module‑level reference/polarity mis‑association as the root cause.\n\nTherefore I hypothesize that the fault is that the control (ambient sensor) module’s main negative/reference input is mis‑wired or mis‑assigned relative to the system ground—i.e., the module is internally referenced to the wrong rail—so correcting the control module’s negative input reference wiring with respect to the system supply rails should restore proper operation.'
